 have <i>bodies much smaller than atoms<\/i> and a very large value for their charge-to-mass ratio.<sup id=\"cite_ref-chemheritage_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/J._J._Thomson#cite_note-chemheritage-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Thus he is credited with the discovery and identification of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Electron\" title=\"Electron\">electron<\/a>; and with the discovery of the first <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Subatomic_particle\" title=\"Subatomic particle\">subatomic particle<\/a>. Thomson is also credited with finding the first evidence for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Isotope\" title=\"Isotope\">isotopes<\/a> of a stable (non-radioactive) element in 1913, as part of his exploration into the composition of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Canal_ray\" title=\"Canal ray\" class=\"mw-redirect\">canal rays<\/a> (positive ions). His experiments to determine the nature of positively charged particles, with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_William_Aston\" title=\"Francis William Aston\">Francis William Aston<\/a>, were the first use of mass spectrometry and led to the development of the mass spectrograph.<sup id=\"cite_ref-chemheritage_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/J._J._Thomson#cite_note-chemheritage-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Thomson was awarded the 1906 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> for the discovery of the electron and for his work on the conduction of electricity in gases.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Nobel1906_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/J._J._Thomson#cite_note-Nobel1906-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Seven of his students, and his son <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Paget_Thomson\" title=\"George Paget Thomson\">George Paget Thomson<\/a>, also became Nobel Prize winners.<\/p>","name":"J. J. Thomson","place_of_birth":"Cheetham Hill ,  Manchester ,  Lancashire ,  England ,  United Kingdom","place_of_death":"Cambridge ,  Cambridgeshire ,  England ,  UK","text":"J. J. Thomson , Physics, 1906","year":1906.0}